HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 769
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Harry Austin of
Chattanooga.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Harry Austin; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Austin was a highly respected journalist and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, a Chattanooga native born on April 2, 1946, Harry Austin began his
journalism career as a high school student, working part time at The Chattanooga Times while
also playing football at Central High School; his early employment with the newspaper enabled
him to attend the University of Chattanooga, now the University of Tennessee at Chattanooga;
and
WHEREAS, after college, Mr. Austin worked for two years as a general assignment
reporter, then as a police reporter, covering crime; after saving enough money for travel, he
spent the next five years exploring Africa, Europe, and Asia, making lifelong friends and
sometimes stopping to work along the way; and
WHEREAS, back in Tennessee, Harry Austin returned to newspaper reporting, covering
general assignments along with the crime and county government beats while demonstrating
the rigor and compassion that would later define his editorial work; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Austin left the newspaper to serve with the Tennessee Valley Authority
in 1980, further broadening his understanding of public institutions and regional issues,
experience he would later bring back into the newsroom; and
WHEREAS, eight years later, Harry Austin returned to The Chattanooga Times as an
opinion writer, and, following the merger of The Chattanooga Times and the Chattanooga Free
HJR0769
010862
- 1 -

Press into today's Chattanooga Times Free Press, he became editor of the newspaper's opinion
page, a post he held with distinction until his retirement in 2013; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Austin received numerous awards and recognitions during his illustrious
career; he was active in the National Conference of Editorial Writers for many years and
participated in the Robert Bosch Stiftung German-American Journalists exchange program
promoting international understanding; and
WHEREAS, Harry Austin's true passion was spending time in the saddle on his quarter
horse, Tango, exploring trails with his friends; he loved the outdoors and appreciated the beauty
of nature, riding in local parks and forests most weekends and often participating in cattle drives
and livestock management in the West; and
WHEREAS, left to cherish his memory are his loving partner, Kristy Huntley; daughters,
Karina Allison and Leslie (Josh) Rust; grandson, Michael Rust; sister, Sybil Clark; brother, Ed
Austin; and a host of extended family members, colleagues, and dear friends; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Austin was preceded in death by his parents, James H. Austin, Sr., and
Oberia Austin; and
WHEREAS, Harry Austin leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Harry Austin, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Austin.
- 2 - 010862

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
